{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535835","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535835"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:00:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:00:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15527"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15527","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15527"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.09,0.51,0.09,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8218"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114733"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8218","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8218"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15527"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96736"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"16"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"7708"},{"type":"tags","id":"11724"},{"type":"tags","id":"12803"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19878"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37094"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37095"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114733","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114733"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA researcher conducts a case-control study investigating whether coffee consumption increases the risk of lung cancer. Initial unadjusted analysis shows that people who drink more than four cups of coffee per day have a significantly higher incidence of lung cancer compared to those who drink less than one cup per day.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes smoking status in this study?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["A continuous variable","An effect modifier","A confounding variable","A dependent variable","An independent variable"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA confounding variable\u003C/strong\u003E meets the three criteria for confounding: it is associated with the exposure (coffee consumption), it is independently associated with the outcome (lung cancer), and it is not on the causal pathway between exposure and outcome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAn effect modifier\u003C/strong\u003E would change the strength of association between coffee and cancer across different levels of smoking. \u003Cstrong\u003EA continuous variable\u003C/strong\u003E refers to a variable that can take any value within a range (like age or weight). \u003Cstrong\u003EA dependent variable\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the outcome being measured (lung cancer in this case). \u003Cstrong\u003EAn independent variable\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the exposure being studied (coffee consumption in this case).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EControlling for smoking is essential to determine whether coffee consumption truly has an independent association with lung cancer risk.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A confounding variable is independently associated with both the exposure and outcome, potentially creating a spurious association.","Confounding variables must be controlled for through study design or statistical analysis to avoid incorrect conclusions.","Smoking is a classic example of confounding in epidemiological studies as it associates with many lifestyle factors and disease outcomes."],"references":["Richardson AM, Joshy G. Deconfounding confounding part 3: controlling for confounding in statistical analyses. Med J Aust. 2020;213(5):209-212.e1.","Motulsky H. Intuitive Biostatistics: A Nonmathematical Guide to Statistical Thinking. 4th ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press Academic US; 2017."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96736"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15527"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96736","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96736"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-19T19:45:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-19T19:46:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8218"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114733"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"16","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/16"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udcca","name":"Biostatistics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relati